reelection and the propensity of state electorates to vote. In doing so, Attacking Judges explores vital dimensions of the conventional wisdom that campaign politics has deleterious consequences for judges, voters, and state judiciaries. Countering the prevailing wisdom with empirically based conclusions, Hall uncovers surprising and important insights, including new revelations on how attack ads influence public engagement with judicial elections and their relative effectiveness in various types of state elections. Attacking Judges is a testament to the power of institutions in American politics and the value of empirical political science research in helping to inform some of the most significant debates on the public agenda. This book's results smartly contest and eradicate many of the fears judicial reformers have about the damaging effects of campaign negativity in modern state supreme court elections.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAdvertising, PoliticalxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aCourts of last resortzUnited StatesxStates. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesxElection. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited StatesxStates. 4aattack advertising. 4aballot rolloff. 4acampaign negativity. 4acampaigns. 4ajudicial elections. 4ajudicial reform. 4anonpartisan elections. 4astate supreme court elections. 4athe incumbency advantage. 4avoter demobilization. 7aLAW / Media & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479309440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804793094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804793094.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles